1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,634
A young painter has a weird smell

2
00:00:01,634 --> 00:00:03,085
coming out of his studio

3
00:00:03,085 --> 00:00:04,552
When friends come to visit

4
00:00:04,552 --> 00:00:06,287
they can barely breathe

5
00:00:06,287 --> 00:00:09,873
The room smells like death Wait

6
00:00:09,873 --> 00:00:11,841
are those actual human body parts

7
00:00:11,841 --> 00:00:12,808
in his studio

8
00:00:12,808 --> 00:00:14,259
Arms and legs

9
00:00:14,259 --> 00:00:15,743
Is that a severed head

10
00:00:15,743 --> 00:00:16,677
on the roof

11
00:00:16,677 --> 00:00:18,211
It's Paris 1818

12
00:00:18,211 --> 00:00:19,479
Napoleon has been gone

13
00:00:19,479 --> 00:00:20,480
for three years

14
00:00:20,480 --> 00:00:22,398
The Bourbon monarchy is back

15
00:00:22,398 --> 00:00:23,265
The art world

16
00:00:23,265 --> 00:00:25,450
is controlled by the Académie led

17
00:00:25,450 --> 00:00:27,985
by David's star student Ingres

18
00:00:27,985 --> 00:00:29,285
and a young artist

19
00:00:29,285 --> 00:00:30,803
named Théodore Géricault

20
00:00:30,803 --> 00:00:33,371
is working on something enormous

21
00:00:33,371 --> 00:00:34,806
something that's going to make

22
00:00:34,806 --> 00:00:37,141
Paris very uncomfortable

23
00:00:37,141 --> 00:00:38,108
Tragically

24
00:00:38,108 --> 00:00:40,109
he'd be dead at thirty two

25
00:00:40,109 --> 00:00:42,027
but his friend also an artist

26
00:00:42,027 --> 00:00:43,728
influenced by him would become

27
00:00:43,728 --> 00:00:45,012
one of the key figures

28
00:00:45,012 --> 00:00:46,563
of French romanticism

29
00:00:46,563 --> 00:00:48,781
His name was Henri Delacroix

30
00:00:48,781 --> 00:00:50,349
This is their story

31
00:00:50,349 --> 00:00:52,367
The story of romantic art

32
00:00:52,367 --> 00:00:53,084
אוקיי Last

33
00:00:53,084 --> 00:00:55,186
time we left David in exile

34
00:00:55,186 --> 00:00:56,503
the most powerful painter

35
00:00:56,503 --> 00:00:58,488
in France banished to Brussels

36
00:00:58,488 --> 00:01:00,339
for voting to kill a king

37
00:01:00,339 --> 00:01:01,306
His student

38
00:01:01,306 --> 00:01:03,191
Ingres was carrying the torch

39
00:01:03,191 --> 00:01:05,126
of the neoclassical tradition

40
00:01:05,126 --> 00:01:06,710
defending line reason

41
00:01:06,710 --> 00:01:08,111
classical subjects

42
00:01:08,111 --> 00:01:09,695
the whole program

43
00:01:09,695 --> 00:01:10,779
mostly from Rome

44
00:01:10,779 --> 00:01:12,597
where he'd been living for years

45
00:01:12,597 --> 00:01:14,298
But the world had changed

46
00:01:14,298 --> 00:01:15,549
Napoleon was gone

47
00:01:15,549 --> 00:01:17,400
The old monarchies were back

48
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:19,001
And an entire generation

49
00:01:19,001 --> 00:01:20,119
had grown up watching

50
00:01:20,119 --> 00:01:21,870
the promises of the Enlightenment

51
00:01:21,870 --> 00:01:23,754
that eighteenth-century belief

52
00:01:23,754 --> 00:01:25,572
that reason and science

53
00:01:25,572 --> 00:01:28,141
could answer everything collapse

54
00:01:28,141 --> 00:01:29,358
Reason was supposed

55
00:01:29,358 --> 00:01:30,592
to fix everything

56
00:01:30,592 --> 00:01:31,643
It didn't

57
00:01:31,643 --> 00:01:33,161
The Revolution was supposed

58
00:01:33,161 --> 00:01:34,228
to bring liberty

59
00:01:34,228 --> 00:01:36,379
It brought mass executions

60
00:01:36,379 --> 00:01:38,114
Napoleon was supposed

61
00:01:38,114 --> 00:01:39,298
to bring order

62
00:01:39,298 --> 00:01:42,183
He brought 20 years of war

63
00:01:42,183 --> 00:01:44,018
So a new generation

64
00:01:44,018 --> 00:01:44,952
started asking

65
00:01:44,952 --> 00:01:46,152
a different question

66
00:01:46,152 --> 00:01:48,054
Not what is true

67
00:01:48,054 --> 00:01:50,322
but what do I feel

68
00:01:50,322 --> 00:01:51,956
That's romanticism

69
00:01:51,956 --> 00:01:53,757
Not a style exactly

70
00:01:53,757 --> 00:01:53,958


71
00:01:53,958 --> 00:01:56,476
More like a shift in what matters

72
00:01:56,476 --> 00:01:57,326
The Enlightenment

73
00:01:57,326 --> 00:01:59,328
said Trust your mind

74
00:01:59,328 --> 00:02:02,313
Romanticism said Trust your gut

75
00:02:02,313 --> 00:02:04,698
your emotions your instincts

76
00:02:04,698 --> 00:02:05,665
The things that

77
00:02:05,665 --> 00:02:07,333
reason can't explain

78
00:02:07,333 --> 00:02:09,234
It wasn't only painting

79
00:02:09,234 --> 00:02:10,819
across music poetry

80
00:02:10,819 --> 00:02:11,886
and philosophy

81
00:02:11,886 --> 00:02:12,086


82
00:02:12,086 --> 00:02:13,937
People were saying the same thing

83
00:02:13,937 --> 00:02:16,155
Reason alone isn't enough

84
00:02:16,155 --> 00:02:17,139
And in art

85
00:02:17,139 --> 00:02:18,590
it starts with a concept

86
00:02:18,590 --> 00:02:20,458
that the Romantics were obsessed

87
00:02:20,458 --> 00:02:23,560
with a concept called the Sublime

88
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:25,028
The sublime is

89
00:02:25,028 --> 00:02:27,263
Okay have you ever stood

90
00:02:27,263 --> 00:02:28,630
at the edge of a cliff

91
00:02:28,630 --> 00:02:30,715
or watched a thunderstorm

92
00:02:30,715 --> 00:02:32,233
roll over the ocean

93
00:02:32,233 --> 00:02:33,433
That feeling

94
00:02:33,433 --> 00:02:34,834
where you're terrified

95
00:02:34,834 --> 00:02:37,303
and amazed at the same time where

96
00:02:37,303 --> 00:02:40,305
you feel tiny and overwhelmed

97
00:02:40,305 --> 00:02:42,022
and somehow more alive

98
00:02:42,022 --> 00:02:43,590
than you've ever been

99
00:02:43,590 --> 00:02:45,141
That's the sublime

100
00:02:45,141 --> 00:02:45,908
The Irish

101
00:02:45,908 --> 00:02:47,743
British philosopher Edmund Burke

102
00:02:47,743 --> 00:02:50,144
defined it in 1750 7

103
00:02:50,144 --> 00:02:51,812
The experience of awe

104
00:02:51,812 --> 00:02:53,997
mixed with terror in the face

105
00:02:53,997 --> 00:02:56,248
of something vast powerful

106
00:02:56,248 --> 00:02:57,799
or too big to grasp

107
00:02:57,799 --> 00:03:00,251
The Romantics didn't want beauty

108
00:03:00,251 --> 00:03:02,069
Beauty is pleasant

109
00:03:02,069 --> 00:03:04,237
Beauty is a painting of a woman

110
00:03:04,237 --> 00:03:05,204
on a swing

111
00:03:05,204 --> 00:03:07,272
The Romantics wanted overwhelm

112
00:03:07,272 --> 00:03:08,290
They wanted art

113
00:03:08,290 --> 00:03:09,240
that made you feel like

114
00:03:09,240 --> 00:03:10,775
you were standing at the edge

115
00:03:10,775 --> 00:03:12,326
of something enormous

116
00:03:12,326 --> 00:03:13,626
And one of the paintings

117
00:03:13,626 --> 00:03:16,045
that captures it best is this one

118
00:03:16,045 --> 00:03:17,729
Caspar David Friedrich

119
00:03:17,729 --> 00:03:20,114
Wanderer above the Sea of Fog

120
00:03:20,114 --> 00:03:22,132
painted around 1818

121
00:03:22,132 --> 00:03:24,133
A man standing on a rocky peak

122
00:03:24,133 --> 00:03:25,518
He's back to us

123
00:03:25,518 --> 00:03:27,152
We can't see his face

124
00:03:27,152 --> 00:03:28,770
We see what he sees

125
00:03:28,770 --> 00:03:30,437
An infinite landscape

126
00:03:30,437 --> 00:03:32,556
of fog and mountains

127
00:03:32,556 --> 00:03:34,423
stretching to the horizon

128
00:03:34,423 --> 00:03:37,409
He's alone completely alone

129
00:03:37,409 --> 00:03:38,193
and the world

130
00:03:38,193 --> 00:03:40,344
in front of him is beautiful

131
00:03:40,344 --> 00:03:43,096
and terrifying and unknowable

132
00:03:43,096 --> 00:03:45,397
That's Romanticism in one image

133
00:03:45,397 --> 00:03:46,515
The individual

134
00:03:46,515 --> 00:03:48,199
confronting the infinite

135
00:03:48,199 --> 00:03:49,667
Friedrich was German

136
00:03:49,667 --> 00:03:51,018
and Romanticism

137
00:03:51,018 --> 00:03:52,702
wasn't just a French thing

138
00:03:52,702 --> 00:03:54,186
Across Europe artists

139
00:03:54,186 --> 00:03:55,871
were moving in this direction

140
00:03:55,871 --> 00:03:57,539
In Britain J.M.W

141
00:03:57,539 --> 00:03:59,190
Turner was doing something

142
00:03:59,190 --> 00:03:59,873
similar

143
00:03:59,873 --> 00:04:02,025
but in a completely different way

144
00:04:02,025 --> 00:04:03,659
Where Friedrich is still

145
00:04:03,659 --> 00:04:06,661
and quiet Turner is all motion

146
00:04:06,661 --> 00:04:09,046
Storms fire light ships

147
00:04:09,046 --> 00:04:10,580
dissolving into the air

148
00:04:10,580 --> 00:04:12,215
His paintings don't ask

149
00:04:12,215 --> 00:04:13,299
to be understood

150
00:04:13,299 --> 00:04:14,683
They overwhelm you

151
00:04:14,683 --> 00:04:17,068
Different approaches same idea

152
00:04:17,068 --> 00:04:19,353
The individual facing forces

153
00:04:19,353 --> 00:04:20,887
bigger than themselves

154
00:04:20,887 --> 00:04:22,672
The romantic painter had a set

155
00:04:22,672 --> 00:04:25,474
of obsessions big crush in nature

156
00:04:25,474 --> 00:04:26,574
The individual lost

157
00:04:26,574 --> 00:04:28,776
in something vast intense color

158
00:04:28,776 --> 00:04:30,894
and dramatic light history myth

159
00:04:30,894 --> 00:04:32,445
and far off places

160
00:04:32,445 --> 00:04:33,829
Basically anything

161
00:04:33,829 --> 00:04:35,647
that felt alive and untamed

162
00:04:35,647 --> 00:04:37,131
compared to the gray routine

163
00:04:37,131 --> 00:04:38,432
of modern Paris

164
00:04:38,432 --> 00:04:39,883
that was the mood

165
00:04:39,883 --> 00:04:40,900
and the painting

166
00:04:40,900 --> 00:04:43,068
that truly announced romanticism

167
00:04:43,068 --> 00:04:43,902
to the world

168
00:04:43,902 --> 00:04:46,988
raw chaotic impossible to ignore

169
00:04:46,988 --> 00:04:48,405
was about to arrive

170
00:04:48,405 --> 00:04:49,956
June 18 16

171
00:04:49,956 --> 00:04:51,040
A French warship

172
00:04:51,040 --> 00:04:52,141
called the Meduse

173
00:04:52,141 --> 00:04:53,742
is sailing to Senegal

174
00:04:53,742 --> 00:04:56,260
On board soldiers settlers

175
00:04:56,260 --> 00:04:57,861
the new colonial governor

176
00:04:57,861 --> 00:04:59,496
And commanding the ship

177
00:04:59,496 --> 00:04:59,996
a captain

178
00:04:59,996 --> 00:05:02,514
named Hugo Duroy de Chaumareys

179
00:05:02,514 --> 00:05:03,765
who had barely sailed

180
00:05:03,765 --> 00:05:05,233
in 20 years

181
00:05:05,233 --> 00:05:06,300
He got the job

182
00:05:06,300 --> 00:05:08,001
through political connections

183
00:05:08,001 --> 00:05:08,185
to the

184
00:05:08,185 --> 00:05:10,303
newly restored Bourbon monarchy

185
00:05:10,303 --> 00:05:12,421
He was by all accounts

186
00:05:12,421 --> 00:05:14,823
spectacularly incompetent

187
00:05:14,823 --> 00:05:16,824
After several days of sailing

188
00:05:16,824 --> 00:05:18,225
not without some mistakes

189
00:05:18,225 --> 00:05:19,426
and incidents

190
00:05:19,426 --> 00:05:20,543
the Meduse got stuck

191
00:05:20,543 --> 00:05:21,494
on a sandbank

192
00:05:21,494 --> 00:05:23,445
off the coast of West Africa

193
00:05:23,445 --> 00:05:23,862
And

194
00:05:23,862 --> 00:05:25,796
there weren't enough lifeboats

195
00:05:25,796 --> 00:05:28,415
So they built a raft hastily

196
00:05:28,415 --> 00:05:30,316
out of whatever they could find

197
00:05:30,316 --> 00:05:30,883
Around

198
00:05:30,883 --> 00:05:33,668
150 people were loaded onto it

199
00:05:33,668 --> 00:05:36,103
Soldiers sailors civilians

200
00:05:36,103 --> 00:05:37,271
The raft was towed

201
00:05:37,271 --> 00:05:38,705
behind the lifeboats

202
00:05:38,705 --> 00:05:41,140
And then the tow ropes were cut

203
00:05:41,140 --> 00:05:42,641
Whether it was deliberate

204
00:05:42,641 --> 00:05:45,026
or accidental is still debated

205
00:05:45,026 --> 00:05:46,994
but the result was the same

206
00:05:46,994 --> 00:05:47,661
A hundred

207
00:05:47,661 --> 00:05:50,613
and 40 7 people on a raft

208
00:05:50,613 --> 00:05:52,597
barely above the waterline

209
00:05:52,597 --> 00:05:54,699
set adrift in the open Atlantic

210
00:05:54,699 --> 00:05:57,034
What followed over thirteen days

211
00:05:57,034 --> 00:05:57,584
is one of the

212
00:05:57,584 --> 00:05:59,685
most horrifying survival stories

213
00:05:59,685 --> 00:06:01,336
in maritime history

214
00:06:01,336 --> 00:06:02,737
By the second night

215
00:06:02,737 --> 00:06:04,005
fights broke out

216
00:06:04,005 --> 00:06:05,539
Men went mad

217
00:06:05,539 --> 00:06:06,973
Some threw themselves

218
00:06:06,973 --> 00:06:07,974
into the sea

219
00:06:07,974 --> 00:06:10,125
By day 4 the survivals

220
00:06:10,125 --> 00:06:11,610
began eating the dead

221
00:06:11,610 --> 00:06:12,777
When the raft was

222
00:06:12,777 --> 00:06:15,029
finally spotted by a passing ship

223
00:06:15,029 --> 00:06:18,197
the Argus 13 days later

224
00:06:18,197 --> 00:06:20,299
15 people were still alive

225
00:06:20,299 --> 00:06:23,151
5 more died shortly after rescue

226
00:06:23,151 --> 00:06:25,002
2 of the survivors Carriard

227
00:06:25,002 --> 00:06:26,987
and Savigny published an account

228
00:06:26,987 --> 00:06:28,888
It became a bestseller

229
00:06:28,888 --> 00:06:30,556
and a political scandal

230
00:06:30,556 --> 00:06:32,957
The incompetent captain was seen

231
00:06:32,957 --> 00:06:34,858
as a symbol of everything wrong

232
00:06:34,858 --> 00:06:36,493
with the restored monarchy

233
00:06:36,493 --> 00:06:37,660
The government tried

234
00:06:37,660 --> 00:06:38,828
to suppress the story

235
00:06:38,828 --> 00:06:40,212
It didn't work

236
00:06:40,212 --> 00:06:43,047
And a 27 year old painter

237
00:06:43,047 --> 00:06:44,748
named Théodore Géricault

238
00:06:44,748 --> 00:06:45,699
read that book

239
00:06:45,699 --> 00:06:47,533
and became obsessed

240
00:06:47,533 --> 00:06:49,101
What Géricault did next

241
00:06:49,101 --> 00:06:52,370
is extraordinary even by well

242
00:06:52,370 --> 00:06:53,787
by any standards

243
00:06:53,787 --> 00:06:55,889
he tracked down the 2 survivors

244
00:06:55,889 --> 00:06:56,923
interviewed them

245
00:06:56,923 --> 00:06:58,040
had them sit for him

246
00:06:58,040 --> 00:06:59,858
and describe everything:

247
00:06:59,858 --> 00:07:01,959
the raft the bodies the weather

248
00:07:01,959 --> 00:07:03,644
the moment they saw the ship

249
00:07:03,644 --> 00:07:05,178
he built a scale model

250
00:07:05,178 --> 00:07:06,879
of the raft in his studio

251
00:07:06,879 --> 00:07:09,198
He went to the morgue repeatedly

252
00:07:09,198 --> 00:07:09,398
and

253
00:07:09,398 --> 00:07:11,115
brought back severed body parts

254
00:07:11,115 --> 00:07:13,617
to study how dead flesh looks

255
00:07:13,617 --> 00:07:14,868
He visited hospitals

256
00:07:14,868 --> 00:07:16,185
to sketch the dying

257
00:07:16,185 --> 00:07:18,253
His friends described the studio

258
00:07:18,253 --> 00:07:19,371
as a slaughterhouse

259
00:07:19,371 --> 00:07:21,472
The smell was unbreathable

260
00:07:21,472 --> 00:07:22,490
he shaved his head

261
00:07:22,490 --> 00:07:24,024
so he wouldn't be tempted

262
00:07:24,024 --> 00:07:25,175
to go outside

263
00:07:25,175 --> 00:07:27,743
He wanted no distractions

264
00:07:27,743 --> 00:07:29,427
18 months

265
00:07:29,427 --> 00:07:31,079
That's how long it took

266
00:07:31,079 --> 00:07:33,147
and the result was a painting

267
00:07:33,147 --> 00:07:36,282
roughly 16 by 23 and a half feet

268
00:07:36,282 --> 00:07:39,417
The Raft of the Medusa 1819

269
00:07:39,417 --> 00:07:40,718
At the bottom

270
00:07:40,718 --> 00:07:43,020
the dead tangled gray

271
00:07:43,020 --> 00:07:44,754
sliding into the water

272
00:07:44,754 --> 00:07:47,423
A father holds his dead son

273
00:07:47,423 --> 00:07:49,424
The bodies are not idealized

274
00:07:49,424 --> 00:07:52,409
They're bloated discolored real

275
00:07:52,409 --> 00:07:53,026
in the middle

276
00:07:53,026 --> 00:07:55,811
the living barely exhausted

277
00:07:55,811 --> 00:07:58,113
desperate clinging to each other

278
00:07:58,113 --> 00:07:59,280
and to the raft

279
00:07:59,280 --> 00:08:00,731
And at the top

280
00:08:00,731 --> 00:08:02,316
a man waving a cloth

281
00:08:02,316 --> 00:08:03,617
He's seen something

282
00:08:03,617 --> 00:08:04,751
on the horizon

283
00:08:04,751 --> 00:08:06,969
There that tiny speck

284
00:08:06,969 --> 00:08:08,119
that's the Argus

285
00:08:08,119 --> 00:08:09,470
That's rescue

286
00:08:09,470 --> 00:08:12,005
It's so small you almost miss it

287
00:08:12,005 --> 00:08:13,506
The entire painting

288
00:08:13,506 --> 00:08:15,308
is built around that gap

289
00:08:15,308 --> 00:08:16,575
between the desperate

290
00:08:16,575 --> 00:08:18,626
waving figure and the almost

291
00:08:18,626 --> 00:08:21,311
invisible ship between hope

292
00:08:21,311 --> 00:08:23,279
and the very real possibility

293
00:08:23,279 --> 00:08:25,164
that hope is an illusion

294
00:08:25,164 --> 00:08:27,132
The ship might not see them

295
00:08:27,132 --> 00:08:28,966
It might sail past

296
00:08:28,966 --> 00:08:30,918
And everyone on this raft

297
00:08:30,918 --> 00:08:31,918
will die

298
00:08:31,918 --> 00:08:33,436
Géricault chose to paint

299
00:08:33,436 --> 00:08:35,321
the most uncertain moment

300
00:08:35,321 --> 00:08:37,656
Not the rescue not the suffering

301
00:08:37,656 --> 00:08:39,423
in its worst the moment

302
00:08:39,423 --> 00:08:41,124
where it could go either way

303
00:08:41,124 --> 00:08:41,808
That's

304
00:08:41,808 --> 00:08:43,876
not a neoclassical painting

