the energy the chaos

608
00:17:34,708 --> 00:17:36,425
the bodies in the streets

609
00:17:36,425 --> 00:17:37,593
moved him deeply

610
00:17:37,593 --> 00:17:39,010
He wrote to his brother

611
00:17:39,010 --> 00:17:40,495
"Since I have not fought

612
00:17:40,495 --> 00:17:42,146
for the glory of my country

613
00:17:42,146 --> 00:17:44,080
at least I will paint for her."

614
00:17:44,080 --> 00:17:47,232
Liberty leading the people 1830

615
00:17:47,232 --> 00:17:49,034
At the center Marianne

616
00:17:49,034 --> 00:17:51,085
the female allegory of France

617
00:17:51,085 --> 00:17:52,369
bare-breasted

618
00:17:52,369 --> 00:17:54,304
holding the tricolor flag

619
00:17:54,304 --> 00:17:55,621
striding forward

620
00:17:55,621 --> 00:17:57,006
over the barricades

621
00:17:57,006 --> 00:17:58,757
She's not a real woman

622
00:17:58,757 --> 00:17:59,941
She's an idea

623
00:17:59,941 --> 00:18:01,909
liberty itself made flesh

624
00:18:01,909 --> 00:18:04,527
Besides her a boy with 2 pistols

625
00:18:04,527 --> 00:18:05,845
He's maybe 12

626
00:18:05,845 --> 00:18:07,629
He's terrified and excited

627
00:18:07,629 --> 00:18:08,747
A man in a top hat

628
00:18:08,747 --> 00:18:09,764
the middle class

629
00:18:09,764 --> 00:18:11,448
A worker in a white shirt

630
00:18:11,448 --> 00:18:12,399
a soldier

631
00:18:12,399 --> 00:18:13,850
People of every class

632
00:18:13,850 --> 00:18:15,668
and age fighting together

633
00:18:15,668 --> 00:18:18,303
And at the bottom the dead lying

634
00:18:18,303 --> 00:18:21,522
tangled half undressed the cost

635
00:18:21,522 --> 00:18:23,490
Now I want you to compare this

636
00:18:23,490 --> 00:18:25,524
to David's political paintings

637
00:18:25,524 --> 00:18:27,726
David was a true believer

638
00:18:27,726 --> 00:18:29,277
He joined the revolution

639
00:18:29,277 --> 00:18:30,077
He voted

640
00:18:30,077 --> 00:18:31,361
He signed warrants

641
00:18:31,361 --> 00:18:33,446
His paintings were tools

642
00:18:33,446 --> 00:18:35,614
of a specific political program

643
00:18:35,614 --> 00:18:38,416
Delacroix didn't do any of that

644
00:18:38,416 --> 00:18:39,550
He painted

645
00:18:39,550 --> 00:18:41,702
the feeling of revolution

646
00:18:41,702 --> 00:18:43,403
The light in his painting

647
00:18:43,403 --> 00:18:44,420
is impossible

648
00:18:44,420 --> 00:18:46,321
It's theatrical dramatic

649
00:18:46,321 --> 00:18:48,039
not how a Paris street

650
00:18:48,039 --> 00:18:50,090
actually looks during a battle

651
00:18:50,090 --> 00:18:52,042
The composition is staged

652
00:18:52,042 --> 00:18:54,160
Marianne is an allegory

653
00:18:54,160 --> 00:18:55,527
not a real person

654
00:18:55,527 --> 00:18:57,495
David painted ideology

655
00:18:57,495 --> 00:18:59,747
Delacroix painted emotion

656
00:18:59,747 --> 00:19:00,647
That might

657
00:19:00,647 --> 00:19:03,032
be the clearest single way to

658
00:19:03,032 --> 00:19:05,567
see the gap between Neoclassicism

659
00:19:05,567 --> 00:19:06,885
and Romanticism

660
00:19:06,885 --> 00:19:08,669
Not the only difference

661
00:19:08,669 --> 00:19:10,220
but one of the deepest

662
00:19:10,220 --> 00:19:12,138
Delacroix had found his voice

663
00:19:12,138 --> 00:19:13,239
painting revolution

664
00:19:13,239 --> 00:19:14,757
and myth in Paris

665
00:19:14,757 --> 00:19:15,874
The next thing

666
00:19:15,874 --> 00:19:17,392
that changed him completely

667
00:19:17,392 --> 00:19:19,660
wouldn't come from Paris at all

668
00:19:19,660 --> 00:19:21,261
In 1832

669
00:19:21,261 --> 00:19:23,145
Delacroix got an invitation

670
00:19:23,145 --> 00:19:24,830
that changed his life

671
00:19:24,830 --> 00:19:26,714
France had sent an official

672
00:19:26,714 --> 00:19:28,682
diplomatic mission to Morocco

673
00:19:28,682 --> 00:19:31,117
and Delacroix was invited

674
00:19:31,117 --> 00:19:32,918
to join as its artist

675
00:19:32,918 --> 00:19:34,002
By this point

676
00:19:34,002 --> 00:19:36,037
his name was significant enough

677
00:19:36,037 --> 00:19:37,405
and his connections

678
00:19:37,405 --> 00:19:39,523
in government circles deep enough

679
00:19:39,523 --> 00:19:40,957
that having him among

680
00:19:40,957 --> 00:19:42,758
carried its own prestige

681
00:19:42,758 --> 00:19:45,243
France had also invaded Algeria

682
00:19:45,243 --> 00:19:47,395
2 years earlier and the whole

683
00:19:47,395 --> 00:19:49,329
trip was a colonial mission

684
00:19:49,329 --> 00:19:50,797
Delacroix was traveling

685
00:19:50,797 --> 00:19:52,081
under its protection

686
00:19:52,081 --> 00:19:55,667
he went and it rewired his brain

687
00:19:55,667 --> 00:19:56,851
He filled notebooks

688
00:19:56,851 --> 00:19:58,619
with sketches watercolors

689
00:19:58,619 --> 00:19:59,503
and notes

690
00:19:59,503 --> 00:20:01,971
He was overwhelmed by the light

691
00:20:01,971 --> 00:20:03,689
the color the architecture

692
00:20:03,689 --> 00:20:04,489
the people

693
00:20:04,489 --> 00:20:06,107
Everything looked different

694
00:20:06,107 --> 00:20:07,007
from Paris

695
00:20:07,007 --> 00:20:08,792
the light sharper the colors

696
00:20:08,792 --> 00:20:10,360
stronger the streets

697
00:20:10,360 --> 00:20:12,494
and people unlike anything

698
00:20:12,494 --> 00:20:14,312
he had ever seen before

699
00:20:14,312 --> 00:20:15,363
Women of Algiers

700
00:20:15,363 --> 00:20:17,915
in their apartment 1834

701
00:20:17,915 --> 00:20:19,782
Painted from memory after

702
00:20:19,782 --> 00:20:22,468
Delacroix was given a rare access

703
00:20:22,468 --> 00:20:24,252
to the private living quarters

704
00:20:24,252 --> 00:20:25,920
of an Algerian household

705
00:20:25,920 --> 00:20:26,937
3 women

706
00:20:26,937 --> 00:20:29,189
in a richly decorated interior

707
00:20:29,189 --> 00:20:30,590
a servant on the right

708
00:20:30,590 --> 00:20:32,841
The colors are warm reds

709
00:20:32,841 --> 00:20:34,809
golds deep greens

710
00:20:34,809 --> 00:20:36,443
The light is soft

711
00:20:36,443 --> 00:20:37,661
It's intimate

712
00:20:37,661 --> 00:20:39,445
You feel like you're in the room

713
00:20:39,445 --> 00:20:41,363
Picasso saw this painting

714
00:20:41,363 --> 00:20:43,798
and was so obsessed with it

715
00:20:43,798 --> 00:20:44,699
that he painted

716
00:20:44,699 --> 00:20:47,217
around 15 variations of it

717
00:20:47,217 --> 00:20:47,801
That's

718
00:20:47,801 --> 00:20:49,669
how deep the influence goes

719
00:20:49,669 --> 00:20:51,337
it's important to mention

720
00:20:51,337 --> 00:20:52,371
that Delacroix

721
00:20:52,371 --> 00:20:55,139
was genuinely fascinated by what

722
00:20:55,139 --> 00:20:56,924
he saw in North Africa

723
00:20:56,924 --> 00:20:59,092
His notebooks are detailed

724
00:20:59,092 --> 00:21:01,076
respectful curious

725
00:21:01,076 --> 00:21:03,661
He wasn't mocking or dismissive

726
00:21:03,661 --> 00:21:06,113
But he was also a European man

727
00:21:06,113 --> 00:21:06,713
traveling

728
00:21:06,713 --> 00:21:08,665
under colonial protection

729
00:21:08,665 --> 00:21:10,449
placing his own fantasies

730
00:21:10,449 --> 00:21:12,634
onto a culture that was

731
00:21:12,634 --> 00:21:14,618
being colonized by his country

732
00:21:14,618 --> 00:21:16,253
The real North Africa

733
00:21:16,253 --> 00:21:17,720
with its own history

734
00:21:17,720 --> 00:21:18,738
its own complexity

735
00:21:18,738 --> 00:21:20,422
complexity was more complicated

736
00:21:20,422 --> 00:21:21,923
than what he painted

737
00:21:21,923 --> 00:21:23,007
This tension

738
00:21:23,007 --> 00:21:24,858
between genuine fascination

739
00:21:24,858 --> 00:21:27,444
and placing your own ideas

740
00:21:27,444 --> 00:21:28,844
onto another culture

741
00:21:28,844 --> 00:21:30,812
is something we'll come back

742
00:21:30,812 --> 00:21:32,780
to later in the series when

743
00:21:32,780 --> 00:21:34,698
we talk about Gauguin in Tahiti

744
00:21:34,698 --> 00:21:37,734
Delacroix is the early

745
00:21:37,734 --> 00:21:39,718
relatively gentle version

746
00:21:39,718 --> 00:21:40,786
of a pattern

747
00:21:40,786 --> 00:21:42,653
that gets much more troubling

748
00:21:42,653 --> 00:21:43,271
later

749
00:21:43,271 --> 00:21:44,471
Women of Algiers

750
00:21:44,471 --> 00:21:46,406
holds both things at once

751
00:21:46,406 --> 00:21:48,941
The painting is extraordinary

752
00:21:48,941 --> 00:21:50,642
The color the warmth

753
00:21:50,642 --> 00:21:52,743
the sense of actually being

754
00:21:52,743 --> 00:21:54,078
inside that room

755
00:21:54,078 --> 00:21:56,513
And it's also a fantasy

756
00:21:56,513 --> 00:21:58,764
a beautiful partial fantasy

757
00:21:58,764 --> 00:21:59,781
made by someone

758
00:21:59,781 --> 00:22:01,883
who had the power to walk in

759
00:22:01,883 --> 00:22:03,434
and the freedom to decide

760
00:22:03,434 --> 00:22:04,484
what it all meant

761
00:22:04,484 --> 00:22:06,052
that doesn't make the painting

762
00:22:06,052 --> 00:22:07,069
less beautiful

763
00:22:07,069 --> 00:22:09,571
It makes the beauty more complicated

764
00:22:09,571 --> 00:22:12,373
North Africa had changed Delacroix's color

765
00:22:12,373 --> 00:22:13,607
his sense of light

766
00:22:13,607 --> 00:22:15,292
his whole way of seeing

767
00:22:15,292 --> 00:22:18,977
Back in Paris one man a poet

768
00:22:18,977 --> 00:22:21,129
understood exactly what had happened

769
00:22:21,129 --> 00:22:22,329
and why it mattered

770
00:22:22,513 --> 00:22:22,646


771
00:22:22,646 --> 00:22:24,364
His name was Charles Baudelaire

772
00:22:24,364 --> 00:22:27,583
In 1846 he wrote a salon review

773
00:22:27,583 --> 00:22:27,983
with

774
00:22:27,983 --> 00:22:29,851
one of the sharpest definitions

775
00:22:29,851 --> 00:22:32,186
of Romanticism ever put on paper

776
00:22:32,486 --> 00:22:32,620


777
00:22:32,620 --> 00:22:35,371
Romanticism is precisely situated

778
00:22:35,371 --> 00:22:37,239
neither in choice of subjects

779
00:22:37,239 --> 00:22:38,974
nor in exact truth

780
00:22:38,974 --> 00:22:40,658
but in a mode of feeling

781
00:22:40,658 --> 00:22:42,076
Not what you paint

782
00:22:42,076 --> 00:22:43,427
not how accurately

783
00:22:43,427 --> 00:22:45,378
but the feeling it creates

784
00:22:45,378 --> 00:22:46,896
Baudelaire praised Delacroix

785
00:22:46,896 --> 00:22:48,046
for decades

786
00:22:48,046 --> 00:22:49,998
calling him the most suggestive

787
00:22:49,998 --> 00:22:51,282
of all painters

788
00:22:51,282 --> 00:22:53,417
Delacroix spent his later years

789
00:22:53,417 --> 00:22:55,418
on major government commissions

790
00:22:55,418 --> 00:22:57,336
Murals at the Palais Bourbon

791
00:22:57,336 --> 00:22:59,054
the Luxembourg Palace

792
00:22:59,054 --> 00:23:00,521
the Chapel of the Holy Angels

793
00:23:00,521 --> 00:23:01,689
at Saint-Sulpice

794
00:23:01,689 --> 00:23:03,273
this might seem surprising

795
00:23:03,273 --> 00:23:05,224
for a painter who had spent years

796
00:23:05,224 --> 00:23:07,242
shocking the Salon but government

797
00:23:07,242 --> 00:23:08,943
commissions work differently

798
00:23:08,943 --> 00:23:10,728
A minister could hire

799
00:23:10,728 --> 00:23:14,464
whoever he chose and by the 1830s

800
00:23:14,464 --> 00:23:15,998
Delacroix was too famous

801
00:23:15,998 --> 00:23:17,049
to keep ignoring

802
00:23:17,049 --> 00:23:18,583
Liberty Leading the People

803
00:23:18,583 --> 00:23:19,434
had helped

804
00:23:19,434 --> 00:23:21,251
however uncomfortable the salon

805
00:23:21,251 --> 00:23:23,536
found his style that painting

806
00:23:23,536 --> 00:23:25,554
had made him a national figure

807
00:23:25,554 --> 00:23:28,289
his late work gets looser freer

808
00:23:28,289 --> 00:23:29,657
almost abstract

809
00:23:29,657 --> 00:23:31,375
The individual brush strokes

810
00:23:31,375 --> 00:23:32,492
become visible

811
00:23:32,492 --> 00:23:34,427
You stop seeing the subject

812
00:23:34,427 --> 00:23:36,895
and start seeing the paint itself

813
00:23:36,895 --> 00:23:38,563
You can see in those murals

814
00:23:38,563 --> 00:23:40,798
the seeds of what's coming next

815
00:23:40,798 --> 00:23:43,433
Impressionism even abstraction

816
00:23:43,433 --> 00:23:44,633
His health declined

817
00:23:44,633 --> 00:23:46,134
through the 1850s

818
00:23:46,134 --> 00:23:47,335
Tuberculosis

819
00:23:47,335 --> 00:23:50,888
He died on August 13th 1863

820
00:23:50,888 --> 00:23:51,805
in Paris

821
00:23:51,805 --> 00:23:53,306
His studio and notebooks

822
00:23:53,306 --> 00:23:53,906
contained

823
00:23:53,906 --> 00:23:56,091
thousands of works studies

824
00:23:56,091 --> 00:23:58,026
sketches finished paintings

825
00:23:58,026 --> 00:23:59,176
And here's the detail

826
00:23:59,176 --> 00:24:00,127
that matters

827
00:24:00,127 --> 00:24:01,928
His funeral was attended

828
00:24:01,928 --> 00:24:04,146
by several of the young painters

829
00:24:04,146 --> 00:24:05,130
who would go on

830
00:24:05,130 --> 00:24:06,981
and become the Impressionists

831
00:24:06,981 --> 00:24:08,216
Bazille was there

832
00:24:08,216 --> 00:24:10,600
Monet and Renoir likely were too

833
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:11,935
They admired him

834
00:24:11,935 --> 00:24:13,519
They saw in his color

835
00:24:13,519 --> 00:24:16,271
his freedom his refusal to submit

836
00:24:16,271 --> 00:24:17,789
to the Académie's rules

837
00:24:17,789 --> 00:24:19,139
a path forward

838
00:24:19,139 --> 00:24:20,957
Delacroix didn't know it

839
00:24:20,957 --> 00:24:22,542
but he was handing the torch

840
00:24:22,542 --> 00:24:23,993
to the next generation

841
00:24:23,993 --> 00:24:24,743
So here's

842
00:24:24,743 --> 00:24:26,428
where Romanticism leaves us

843
00:24:26,428 --> 00:24:28,812
It said "Feel everything

844
00:24:28,812 --> 00:24:30,847
The mind isn't enough

845
00:24:30,847 --> 00:24:32,682
Reason isn't enough

846
00:24:32,682 --> 00:24:34,916
Art should overwhelm you

847
00:24:34,916 --> 00:24:36,367
with beauty with terror

848
00:24:36,367 --> 00:24:38,402
with passion with the sublime."

849
00:24:38,402 --> 00:24:39,703
And it delivered

850
00:24:39,703 --> 00:24:40,920
Géricault's The Raft

851
00:24:40,920 --> 00:24:43,239
of the Medusa is overwhelming

852
00:24:43,239 --> 00:24:44,556
Delacroix's Liberty

853
00:24:44,556 --> 00:24:45,757
Leading the People

854
00:24:45,757 --> 00:24:47,174
is electrifying

855
00:24:47,174 --> 00:24:48,775
Turner's The Burning

856
00:24:48,775 --> 00:24:49,910
of the Houses of Lords

857
00:24:49,910 --> 00:24:52,144
and Commons is staggering

858
00:24:52,144 --> 00:24:54,346
Friedrich's Wanderer is sublime

859
00:24:54,346 --> 00:24:55,630
But there is a risk

860
00:24:55,630 --> 00:24:57,081
If you chase feeling

861
00:24:57,081 --> 00:24:58,915
if you abandon the rules

862
00:24:58,915 --> 00:25:00,383
where do you stop

863
00:25:00,383 --> 00:25:02,268
Romanticism opened a door

864
00:25:02,268 --> 00:25:04,002
that couldn't be closed

865
00:25:04,002 --> 00:25:06,020
What kind of art can be made

866
00:25:06,020 --> 00:25:07,571
when you stop following

867
00:25:07,571 --> 00:25:09,206
the Académie's guidelines

868
00:25:09,206 --> 00:25:11,007
remember the Salon's hierarchy

869
00:25:11,007 --> 00:25:13,342
of subjects what was considered

870
00:25:13,342 --> 00:25:14,776
the most noble and

871
00:25:14,776 --> 00:25:16,560
what sat at the very bottom

872
00:25:16,560 --> 00:25:17,728
of the accepted list

873
00:25:17,728 --> 00:25:19,095
of painting topics

874
00:25:19,095 --> 00:25:20,346
can you imagine what

875
00:25:20,346 --> 00:25:22,231
kind of art could be made when

876
00:25:22,231 --> 00:25:24,399
all of those rules are rejected

877
00:25:24,399 --> 00:25:26,117
What kind of new creative

878
00:25:26,117 --> 00:25:27,468
even crazy ideas

879
00:25:27,468 --> 00:25:28,802
could come into the world

880
00:25:28,802 --> 00:25:30,753
There is still so much more

881
00:25:30,753 --> 00:25:31,470
to come

882
00:25:31,470 --> 00:25:32,521
But for now

883
00:25:32,521 --> 00:25:34,105
let's continue with this

884
00:25:34,105 --> 00:25:36,740
What if instead of painting gods

885
00:25:36,740 --> 00:25:38,425
and heroes and revolutions

886
00:25:38,425 --> 00:25:41,560
and fantasies you just looked

887
00:25:41,560 --> 00:25:43,712
What if you painted the world

888
00:25:43,712 --> 00:25:45,563
exactly as it was not

889
00:25:45,563 --> 00:25:47,080
as you wished it was not

890
00:25:47,080 --> 00:25:48,315
as it made you feel

891
00:25:48,315 --> 00:25:50,433
Just what's there

892
00:25:50,433 --> 00:25:52,067
The ugly parts

893
00:25:52,067 --> 00:25:54,368
the boring parts reality

894
00:25:54,368 --> 00:25:55,202
as it is

895
00:25:55,202 --> 00:25:57,587
what if you painted a funeral

896
00:25:57,587 --> 00:25:58,888
in a small town

897
00:25:58,888 --> 00:26:01,990
with ugly people and a dog but

898
00:26:01,990 --> 00:26:04,258
at the size of a history painting

899
00:26:04,258 --> 00:26:05,376
What if

900
00:26:05,376 --> 00:26:07,043
you built your own exhibition

901
00:26:07,043 --> 00:26:09,145
hall when the salon rejected you

902
00:26:09,145 --> 00:26:10,529
and you told the entire art

903
00:26:10,529 --> 00:26:12,530
establishment to go to hell

904
00:26:12,530 --> 00:26:14,632
One man did exactly that

905
00:26:14,632 --> 00:26:17,033
